Two things review would have missed
parse_table was secretly re-reading m_hdr. Lines 117–118 pulled count and sts back out of the header buffer while parsing the table. The old design kept both buffers alive at once; one general blob can't. Silent breakage — the counts would have been read from table bytes and produced plausible garbage. Now stashed at header-parse time.
The tail of parse_table is format-independent. Sort into stream order, NSZ key check, container_size(), NCA count, enter Phase::Data — none of it cares what the table looked like. Extracted as finalize_entries(). Below that line, nothing knows whether the bytes came from a PFS0 or an XCI's secure partition, which is what makes 4c a front-end rather than a rewrite.
The shape is now one rule: collect N bytes at absolute offset X, run step S, discarding everything in between. want() refuses a backwards offset outright — a stream can't rewind, and asking is a caller bug, not a runtime condition.
